John — That Garmond Romein No. 1 is certainly a fine example of Fleischman’s art. Are you sure this is the same as your Long Primer Roman No. 48? John A. Lane’s notes to the 1768 specimen list this Garmond Romein No. 1 as Enschedé matrix inventory no. 56.

Also, I’m not sure that particular face is the best example of what Fournier was thinking of when labeling his “dans le goût Hollandois” cuts. I think that what Fournier perceived as the Dutch penchant for narrow economy is better exemplified in Fleischman’s second and third Descendiaan Romans, for instance:

 ![](http://web.archive.org/web/20100103030326im_/http:/typophile.com/files/Fleischman_Desc_6383.png)

&nbsp;  
&nbsp;  
Hrant — In support of my contention that Fournier’s _goût Hollandois_ was focused on narrowness, I offer these examples from 1995 facsimile of the 1766 _Manuel Typographique_:

 ![](http://web.archive.org/web/20100103030326im_/http:/typophile.com/files/Fournier_PhilGoutHoll_4839.png)

&nbsp;  
(The French Philosophie is approximately the same size as the Dutch Descendiaan.)

 ![](http://web.archive.org/web/20100103030326im_/http:/typophile.com/files/Fournier_CiceroGoutHoll_5289.png)

&nbsp;  
In this example (Cicéro is the next size larger), you can see that Fournier uses _gros œil_ (large eye) to designate the larger x-height, adding _dans le goût Hollandois_ for the narrower variation. Fournier also offers a variety of _petit œil_ and _œil moyen_ cuts in different sizes.

I do think Fournier exaggerates that so-called “Dutch” quality.
